# LID L0 — linked-intent discipline

> Extends `submodules/lid-pi-extension/kit/LID-WORKFLOW.md` — workspace-specific trigger.
> Full workflow, phase templates, and cascade rules: read that file when planning
> a change. This rule is the always-on reminder; the kit file is the depth.

Intent is the artifact. Changes are output. When requirements and implementation
disagree, requirements win — fix the change or deliberately update the intent
and cascade.

## Scale intent work to change size

**Touch** (1–2 files, obvious scope)
Intent lives in the commit message. One sentence: what problem does this solve?
If you can't write it, the scope is larger than it appears.

**Change** (3–5 files, OR any new command / skill / rule / configuration)
Write a one-paragraph Intent Note before touching any files.
State the problem, not the solution. Stop for acknowledgment before proceeding.
Template: `submodules/lid-pi-extension/kit/templates/INTENT.md`

**Restructure** (5+ files, new directories, or architectural shifts)
Walk the full arrow — Intent → Design Note → Acceptance Criteria → Change.
Stop for review after each step. No changes until Acceptance Criteria are approved.
Templates: `submodules/lid-pi-extension/kit/templates/`

## Spar the intent, not the implementation

Adversarial review at the Intent level — before design is locked in — is more
valuable than review after execution. Run `/spar` against the Intent Note for
any Restructure-level change.

## Bypasses

Warn when a change skips the appropriate level. Do not block — make the cost
visible and honor the user's decision.
